Scottish private schools keep track records of academic excellence, and this was continued in 2018 with overwhelming test results, which were further strengthened by each student and collective success in sports, arts, music as well as hard work.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Private School Board (SCIS) strive to provide the best services for the students and parents.
The independent school aims to prepare its students for advanced and higher education, careers of their choice, and their role as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement the school curriculum as expected, we see modern language continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in many schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, your speech will get into his head.
If you talk to him in his language then your speech will go into his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's latest exam, we can see that language is at the top of the league table with the highest grades of graduation in a self-governing school.
A total of 68 percent of students who learn foreign languages get an A Plus.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools that show that 72 percent of students get an A Plus in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learn German, 69 percent of those who learn French and 63 percent who learn Spanish also get an A.
This suggests that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an important skill that will certainly be required by children and adolescents in the future.
Today languages, as a selection of subjects, are held in the same standard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the modern school curriculum and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the British Employment and Skills Service in 2014 found that of some reasons why the workmen should continue to struggle to fill the vacancy, 17 percent why is the lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are further encouraged to prepare youths for their future careers.
With increased employment opportunities that require language skills, these skills are important in the global world.
Whatever one’s choice of career, if they have learned a second language, in the future they will experience the real benefits of having this kind of lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with residents from a foreign country would automatically make a multilingualist excel in competition.
According to a YouGov poll on over 4,000 English adults in 2013, 75 percent of them did not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct the conversation and French became the only spoken language in two percentage digits, which was 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching for children today is important for now.
Having a multilingual ability, especially the language of countries with a growing economy, will equip children with better opportunities to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach the language considered the most important in England for the next few years, which is 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest may be, there will always be a number of languages that can be chosen in an independent school, with an expert teaching staff in this field.
Scottish independent schools are intended to provide learning environments that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever happens in the future.
It cannot be denied that today, in a global business environment, language will always be an important aspect of determining the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern language should really be regarded as "international communication skills."
The self-governing school will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence for Scottish youths.
Il faut bien le faire.
