Red Tide breaking news: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Recent reports from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission show a general decline in Red Tide concentration for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven build-up conditions were reported from areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which signified a decrease in concentration.
A group of Red Tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the southern Lee area.
Groups can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough area, but at some sites relative to last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the Pasco region.
Moderate concentrations on or off the coast of the Pinellas region have been reported in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Hillsborough region, background to high concentrations in the Manatee region, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of the Sarasota region, background to moderate concentrations in the Charlotte region, background to high concentrations on or offshore Lee region, and low concentrations in the Collier region.
Respiratory irritability continues to be reported from the regions of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida during last week.
